<subSubSection id="B2FDE6E3906FFFF1FF42FB2EFE1041EF" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="157" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FA58B568906FFFF2FF42FB2EFD074155" blockId="5.[140,1108,1082,1671]" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906FFFF2FF42FB2EFE87413C" author="Muona J" box="[185,348,1258,1284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" pagination="225 - 246" refId="ref10932" refString="Muona J (1991) Th e North European and British species of the genus Meotica Mulsant &amp; Rey (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Deutsche entomologische Zeitschrift N. F. 38: 225 - 246." type="book chapter" year="1991">Muona (1991</bibRefCitation>
, 239) wrote, “Small aleocharine species are often regarded as difficult to identify. However, it is doubtful (whether) there exists a species with a more confused history (than) that of 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906FFFF2FE0CFAF5FD564172" baseAuthorityName="Knoch in Gravenhorst" baseAuthorityYear="1806" box="[503,653,1328,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FE0CFAF5FD564172" box="[503,653,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">Meotica exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.” Prior reports of its presence in North America have proven to be no exception to this rule.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA58B568906FFFF2FF42FAB3FB8F42BF" blockId="5.[140,1108,1082,1671]" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">
It appears to have first been reported in North America by 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906FFFF2FCA1FAB3FC3141A9" author="Leng CW" box="[858,1002,1399,1425]" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" refId="ref10353" refString="Leng CW (1920) Catalogue of the Coleoptera of America north of Mexico. John D. Sherman, Jr., Mount Vernon, New York, 470 pp." type="book" year="1920">Leng (1920)</bibRefCitation>
followed by 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906FFFF2FF49FA5EFD91418C" author="Bernhauer M &amp; Scheerpeltz O" box="[178,586,1433,1460]" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" pagination="499 - 988" refId="ref9183" refString="Bernhauer M, Scheerpeltz O (1926) Staphylinidae VI. In: Junk W, Schenkling S (Eds) Coleopterum Catalogus, Pars 82. W. Junk, Berlin, 499 - 988." type="book chapter" year="1926">Bernhauer and Scheerpeltz (1926)</bibRefCitation>
. Th ese specimens were examined by 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906FFFF2FBFAFA5EFED241EF" author="Seevers CH" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" pagination="1 - 289" refId="ref11215" refString="Seevers CH (1978) A generic and tribal revision of the North American Aleocharinae (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Fieldiana Zoology 71: 1 - 289." type="journal article" year="1978">Seevers (1978: 79)</bibRefCitation>
who wrote, “Th e record of 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906FFFF2FDA9FA7AFC8741EF" authority="Erichson" authorityName="Erichson" box="[594,860,1469,1495]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FDA9FA7AFD3041EF" box="[594,747,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">Meotica exilis</emphasis>
Erichson
</taxonomicName>
(a European species) in Maine (E. Machias, and 
<collectingCountry id="82F0F5F8906FFFF2FE2EFA24FDC041C3" box="[469,539,1504,1531]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">Wales</collectingCountry>
) is 
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FDB3FA24FD7341C2" box="[584,680,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">probably</emphasis>
(emphasis added) a valid one. I examined the specimens in the Bernhauer collection on which the record was based and found that they do belong to 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906FFFF2FDD9F9E3FDA04278" authorityName="Mulsant &amp; Rey" authorityYear="1873" box="[546,635,1575,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FDD9F9E3FDA04278" box="[546,635,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">Meotica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and are 
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FD17F9E2FC974278" box="[748,844,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">probably</emphasis>
(emphasis added) 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906FFFF2FBD0F9E3FF7F425C" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FBD0F9E3FF7F425C" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These specimens 
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FE86F98EFE06425C" box="[381,477,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">probably</emphasis>
(emphasis added) represent an introduction.” 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906FFFF2FBFBF98EFEC042BF" author="Muona J" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" pagination="227 - 231" refId="ref10904" refString="Muona J (1984) Review of Palaearctic Aleocharinae also occurring in North America (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Entomologica Scandinavica 15: 227 - 231." type="journal article" year="1984">Muona (1984: 228)</bibRefCitation>
did not accept the validity of this record noting that, “ 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906FFFF2FC3DF9AAFBC442BF" authorityName="Mulsant &amp; Rey" authorityYear="1873" box="[966,1055,1646,1671]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="156" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C893697A906FFFF2FC3DF9AAFBC442BF" box="[966,1055,1646,1671]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="156">Meotica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA58B568906CFFF1FF77FF62FDE145C5" blockId="6.[140,692,166,1037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
difficult genus with many species and Seevers’ (1978) statement is quite vague.” 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FDF0FF0EFD6F44DC" author="Muona J" box="[523,692,202,228]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="227 - 231" refId="ref10904" refString="Muona J (1984) Review of Palaearctic Aleocharinae also occurring in North America (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Entomologica Scandinavica 15: 227 - 231." type="journal article" year="1984">Muona (1984)</bibRefCitation>
also pointed out that specimens identified as 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FF77FED5FEF84512" box="[140,291,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FF77FED5FEF84512" box="[140,291,272,298]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Meotica exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Fenyes from Pasadena, 
<collectingRegion id="38237B8A906CFFF1FDA2FED4FF6B4575" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">California</collectingRegion>
(deposited in various European collections and at the FMNH), are in fact a species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FF2EFEBEFDDA45AC" authority=", Casey. Despite" authorityName="Casey. Despite" box="[213,513,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Thecturota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FF2EFEBEFE9045AC" box="[213,331,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Thecturota</emphasis>
, Casey. Despite
</taxonomicName>
this tenuous or erroneous evidence, 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FE85FE5AFE3A458F" box="[382,481,413,439]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FE85FE5AFE3A458F" box="[382,481,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">M. exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has continued to be included in the North America fauna in such recent compendiums as Ashe (2000).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA58B568906CFFF1FF42FDC2FE1B4035" blockId="6.[140,692,166,1037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
The Bernhauer collection is now deposited in the Field Museum of Natural History (FMNH). Margaret Th ayer kindly checked the collection and wrote (pers. comm.) that she was able to find one pin with the label: “E. Machias,/ Me.// June//[white circle]// 
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FE70FD72FDA446E8" bold="true" box="[395,639,694,720]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FE70FD72FDFA46E8" authority="Grvh." authorityName="Grvh." box="[395,545,694,720]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">exilis Grvh.</taxonomicName>
/Fenyes
</emphasis>
/det. Bernhauer//Chicago NHMus/M.Bernhauer/”. The text in boldface is in Bernhauer’s writing, apparently relaying Fenyes as the source of the specimen, the identification, or perhaps both. However, there is no longer any specimen on the pin; the card point has been cut off. There is also no specimen from “ 
<collectingCountry id="82F0F5F8906CFFF1FE46FC69FDDD47FF" box="[445,518,941,967]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Wales</collectingCountry>
, Maine” in the FMNH collection and the present disposition of this specimen is unknown.
</paragraph>
<caption id="AE98E5E0906CFFF1FD22FC10FC3F4032" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773945" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3773945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773945/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" startId="6.[729,763,980,1002]" targetBox="[741,1094,177,931]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph id="FA58B568906CFFF1FD22FC10FC3F4032" blockId="6.[729,1108,980,1034]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FD22FC10FCF947D2" bold="true" box="[729,802,980,1002]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Fig. 3.</emphasis>
Dorsal habitus photograph of 
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FD22FC31FC814031" box="[729,858,1012,1034]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FD22FC31FC8E4031" box="[729,853,1012,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">Meotica exilis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Scale = 
<quantity id="3D1F188D906CFFF1FC5EFC30FC3B4032" box="[933,992,1012,1034]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="FA58B568906CFFF1FF42FBD2FF1C4086" blockId="6.[140,1108,1046,1671]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
Thus, all prior reports of this species in North America appear to have been based on misidentifications, or can no longer be verified because voucher specimens can no longer be located. Th erefore, the present specimens from 
<collectingRegion id="38237B8A906CFFF1FF35FB45FE8240A2" box="[206,345,1152,1179]" country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
constitute the first verifiable records of this species on the continent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA58B568906CFFF1FF42FB02FE1041EF" blockId="6.[140,1108,1046,1671]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
The authority of the specific name of 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FD9FFB03FD1840D8" box="[612,707,1222,1248]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FD9FFB03FD1840D8" box="[612,707,1222,1248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">M. exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been in doubt. It has been referred to as 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FED3FB2EFD50413C" authority="(Erichson, 1839: 333)" baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityPageNumber="333" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[296,651,1258,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FED3FB2EFE5C413C" box="[296,391,1258,1284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">M. exilis</emphasis>
(Erichson, 1839: 333)
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FD3EFB2EFC98413C" author="Leng CW" box="[709,835,1258,1284]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" refId="ref10353" refString="Leng CW (1920) Catalogue of the Coleoptera of America north of Mexico. John D. Sherman, Jr., Mount Vernon, New York, 470 pp." type="book" year="1920">Leng 1920</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FCABFB2EFEDF411F" author="Bernhauer M &amp; Scheerpeltz O" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="499 - 988" refId="ref9183" refString="Bernhauer M, Scheerpeltz O (1926) Staphylinidae VI. In: Junk W, Schenkling S (Eds) Coleopterum Catalogus, Pars 82. W. Junk, Berlin, 499 - 988." type="book chapter" year="1926">Bernhauer and Scheerpeltz 1926</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FEF4FAC9FDFA4110" author="Moore I &amp; Legner EF" box="[271,545,1293,1320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="1 - 514" refId="ref10837" refString="Moore I, Legner EF (1975) A Catalogue of the Staphylinidae of America North of Mexico (Coleoptera). University of California Division of Agricultural Sciences Special Publication 3015: 1 - 514." type="journal article" year="1975">Moore and Legner 1975</bibRefCitation>
); and 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FD9FFACAFC774110" authority="(Gravenhorst, 1806)" baseAuthorityName="Gravenhorst" baseAuthorityYear="1806" box="[612,940,1293,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FD9FFACAFD1A411F" box="[612,705,1293,1319]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">M. exilis</emphasis>
(Gravenhorst, 1806)
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FC42FAC9FB95411F" author="Seevers CH" box="[953,1102,1293,1319]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="1 - 289" refId="ref11215" refString="Seevers CH (1978) A generic and tribal revision of the North American Aleocharinae (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Fieldiana Zoology 71: 1 - 289." type="journal article" year="1978">Seevers 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FF77FAF4FEE44172" author="Smetana A" box="[140,319,1328,1354]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="353 - 494" refId="ref11357" refString="Smetana A (2004 a) Subfamily Aleocharinae Fleming, 1921: In: Lobl I, Smetana A (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Vol. 2. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 353 - 494." type="book chapter" year="2004">Smetana 2004a</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FEA9FAF5FE204172" author="Muona J" box="[338,507,1328,1355]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="225 - 246" refId="ref10932" refString="Muona J (1991) Th e North European and British species of the genus Meotica Mulsant &amp; Rey (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Deutsche entomologische Zeitschrift N. F. 38: 225 - 246." type="book chapter" year="1991">Muona (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, however, argued that the species should be called 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FBC9FAF5FDB24156" authority="(Knoch in Gravenhorst, 1806: 153)" baseAuthorityName="Knoch in Gravenhorst" baseAuthorityPageNumber="153" baseAuthorityYear="1806" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FBC9FAF5FF194155" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">M. exilis</emphasis>
(Knoch in Gravenhorst, 1806: 153)
</taxonomicName>
. Although Gravenhorst cited many Knoch manuscript names without crediting Knoch (thus making Gravenhorst the author), the case of 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FEF2FA5EFEBC418C" baseAuthorityName="Knoch in Gravenhorst" baseAuthorityYear="1806" box="[265,359,1434,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FEF2FA5EFEBC418C" box="[265,359,1434,1460]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">M. exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an exception to the rule because Gravenhorst explicitly credited Knoch with the description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B2FDE6E3906CFFF1FF42FA25FCF942BF" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FA58B568906CFFF1FF42FA25FCF942BF" blockId="6.[140,1108,1046,1671]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FF42FA25FE9441C2" baseAuthorityName="Knoch in Gravenhorst" baseAuthorityYear="1806" box="[185,335,1504,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Meotica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FF42FA25FE9441C2" box="[185,335,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Meotica exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found throughout Europe and northern Asia. It occurs in many kinds of moist situations, preferring rich soils and frequenting shores with dense vegetation and is abundant in leaf-litter under 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FD6BF9E2FD1D4278" authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[656,710,1574,1600]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FD6BF9E2FD1D4278" box="[656,710,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bushes and has been collected in 
<taxonomicName id="3DE7CEEB906CFFF1FF77F98EFF24425C" authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[140,255,1610,1636]" class="Sphagnopsida" family="Sphagnaceae" genus="Sphagnum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sphagnales" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C893697A906CFFF1FF77F98EFF24425C" box="[140,255,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Sphagnum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bogs (
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FEB3F98EFE39425C" author="Muona J" box="[328,482,1610,1636]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="225 - 246" refId="ref10932" refString="Muona J (1991) Th e North European and British species of the genus Meotica Mulsant &amp; Rey (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Deutsche entomologische Zeitschrift N. F. 38: 225 - 246." type="book chapter" year="1991">Muona 1991</bibRefCitation>
). A dorsal habitus photograph is provided in 
<figureCitation id="62DCA9ED906CFFF1FC25F98EFBFA425C" box="[990,1057,1610,1636]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[729,763,980,1002]" captionTargetBox="[741,1094,177,931]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[726,1110,165,942]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Dorsal habitus photograph of Meotica exilis. Scale = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773945/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="157">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
. For illustrations of the genitalia see 
<bibRefCitation id="9E76C899906CFFF1FE0BF9A9FCC542BF" author="Klimaszewski J &amp; Assing V &amp; Majka CG &amp; Pelletier G &amp; Webster RP &amp; Langor D" box="[496,798,1645,1671]" pageId="6" pageNumber="157" pagination="54 - 79" refId="ref10118" refString="Klimaszewski J, Assing V, Majka CG, Pelletier G, Webster RP, Langor D (2007) Records of adventive aleocharine beetles found in Canada (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). Th e Canadian Entomologist 139: 54 - 79." type="journal article" year="2007">Klimaszewski et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
